### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

With signal inputs, there is no clean primitive for "run code once after inputs are set." The current workaround is using `effect()` with `untracked()`:

```typescript
constructor() {
  effect(() => untracked(() => {
    // code that needs inputs to be set
  }));
}
```

This is awkward because:
- `effect()` is designed for reactive side effects, not one-time initialization
- `untracked()` is required to prevent accidental signal tracking
- The pattern contradicts the reactive nature of effects

The signals era provides clean replacements for most lifecycle hooks:

**`ngOnChanges`** ‚Üí `computed()` / `effect()`
```typescript
// Before (ngOnChanges)
@Input() firstName: string;
@Input() lastName: string;
fullName: string;

ngOnChanges() {
  this.fullName = `${this.firstName} ${this.lastName}`;
}

// After (signals)
firstName = input('');
lastName = input('');
fullName = computed(() => `${this.firstName()} ${this.lastName()}`);
```

**`ngOnDestroy`** ‚Üí `DestroyRef.onDestroy()`
```typescript
// Before (ngOnDestroy)
ngOnDestroy() {
  this.cleanup();
}

// After (signals era)
constructor() {
  inject(DestroyRef).onDestroy(() => this.cleanup());
}
```

**`ngOnInit`** ‚Üí ???

There is currently no signals-era equivalent for `ngOnInit`. The only workaround is the awkward `effect(() => untracked(...))` pattern.


### Proposed solution


Introduce an `InitRef` (or similar) injectable that provides an `onInit()` callback, mirroring `DestroyRef.onDestroy()`:

```typescript
constructor() {
  inject(InitRef).onInit(() => {
    // runs once after inputs are set
  });
  inject(DestroyRef).onDestroy(() => {
    // cleanup
  });
}
```

This would:
- Provide a non-reactive primitive for one-time initialization
- Complete the signals-era lifecycle API alongside `DestroyRef`
- Eliminate the `effect(() => untracked(...))` workaround


### Alternatives considered

The current workaround is using `effect()` with `untracked()`:

```typescript
constructor() {
  effect(() => untracked(() => {
    // code that needs inputs to be set
  }));
}
```

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

If you don't return anything from the `computed` signal, no one will complain about it. There will be no compilation or runtime errors.

It is, however, likely a mistake which will lead to incorrect behavior.

```ts
user = signal({
  firstName: 'Lightning',
  lastName: 'McQueen',
});

fullName = computed(() => {
  // Oops, I forgot to add return
  `${this.user().firstName} ${this.user().lastName}`;
});
```

```html
Hi, {{ fullName() }},
```

### Proposed solution

I cannot think of a legitimate reason not to return anything from the computed signal, so it seems like it should be typed to exclude `void` from the list of types it accepts.

### Alternatives considered

`@typescript-eslint/no-unused-expressions` can help, but it only catches simple cases.
